          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 50 days of streaming, editing, and meeting workflows</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Elgato Stream Deck MK.2</strong> is the best macro pad for streamers and power users. The 15 LCD keys display custom icons and live app states, Smart Profiles switch automatically when you change apps, and Multi Actions trigger complex sequences from one press. At $149 it is expensive, and the wired-only design limits placement, but for anyone who automates repetitive workflows daily, it pays for itself in saved clicks.
      </div>

      <p>Elgato launched the original Stream Deck in 2017 and turned a niche streaming tool into a mainstream productivity device. The MK.2, released in 2021, is a minor refresh — the same 15 LCD keys, the same software, but a detachable USB-C cable and a redesigned stand. We bought the MK.2 at retail and spent 50 days using it for streaming, video editing, and remote meeting controls to see whether the $149 asking price still holds up in 2026.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against other macro pads and macro-capable keyboards, see our <a href="/reviews/best-mechanical-keyboard-work/">best mechanical keyboard for work</a> roundup. If you want a productivity mouse to pair with the Stream Deck, the <a href="/reviews/logitech-mx-master-3s-review/">Logitech MX Master 3S review</a> covers a strong option.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>The LCD Keys: The Defining Feature</h3>
      <p>The Stream Deck's defining feature is its 15 customizable LCD keys, each a small color display that can show static icons, animated GIFs, or live app states. A key that mutes your microphone can display a muted or unmuted icon depending on the current state; a key that switches OBS scenes can show a thumbnail of the active scene. The visual feedback is what separates the Stream Deck from a $30 macro keypad with printed labels — you always know what a key will do before you press it.</p>

      <p>In our 50-day test, we used the LCD keys for OBS scene switching, microphone muting, sound effects, app launching, and Premiere Pro shortcuts. The keys are bright and readable from a typical desk viewing angle, and the backlight dims automatically in low light via a built-in ambient sensor. The keys have a firm, tactile click with about 2mm of travel — they feel like mechanical switches, not touchscreens, which is important for confident pressing without looking.</p>

      <p>The LCD pixels are sealed behind a glossy plastic cover that is easy to wipe clean but picks up fingerprints. After 50 days of daily use, we noticed minor smudging on the most-pressed keys, but no scratches or dead pixels. The keys are not user-replaceable — if a pixel dies, you are covered by Elgato's two-year warranty, but outside of warranty, the device is effectively bricked for that key. This is a sealed, integrated product, not a modular one.</p>

      <h3>Smart Profiles: Automatic App Switching</h3>
      <p>The single most useful software feature is Smart Profiles, which switch the 15-key layout automatically when the focused app changes. You can set up a separate profile for OBS, Photoshop, Premiere Pro, Discord, and your web browser, and the keys will relabel themselves with the relevant shortcuts for each app. In our testing, switching was instant and reliable about 95% of the time — occasionally the software missed a focus change, and we had to click back into the app to trigger the switch.</p>

      <p>Setting up profiles takes time, but Elgato provides templates for popular apps, and the community shares profile packs for free. We downloaded a Premiere Pro profile pack with 45 pre-built actions across three folders, which saved us hours of setup. The Elgato Marketplace (in-app) also sells premium icon packs and profile packs, though most users will be fine with the free community content.</p>

      <p>The software supports nested folders, so a single key can open a folder of 15 more actions, and that folder can open another folder, and so on. In practice, nesting beyond two levels gets confusing — you lose track of where you are. Most users settle on one main profile per app with one or two folders of secondary actions. The 15-key limit is the main reason to consider the XL version, which doubles the key count for $70 more.</p>

      <h3>Multi Actions: Macro Sequences</h3>
      <p>Multi Actions are the power-user feature that justifies the Stream Deck for non-streamers. A Multi Action triggers a sequence of up to 32 steps from a single keypress — launch an app, wait 2 seconds, open a specific file, switch audio output, mute the mic, and start a screen recording, all from one tap. We built a "Start Meeting" Multi Action that opens Zoom, mutes the mic, switches audio to headphones, and launches our notes app, saving us about 30 seconds of clicking before every call.</p>

      <p>Multi Actions support delays, conditional logic (via plugins), and chaining across multiple actions. The learning curve is moderate — building a complex sequence takes 10 to 20 minutes the first time, but the interface is drag-and-drop and the documentation is solid. Once built, Multi Actions are reliable; we ran our meeting-start sequence 40+ times over the test period without a failure.</p>

      <p>The plugin ecosystem extends Multi Actions to hundreds of third-party apps. There are plugins for Home Assistant (smart home control), Spotify (play specific playlists), Twitch (chat interactions), Philips Hue (lighting scenes), and most major video editors. Most plugins are free and community-maintained, though quality varies — we tested a few that crashed the Elgato software and had to be removed. Stick to well-reviewed plugins and you will be fine.</p>

      <h3>Build Quality and Design</h3>
      <p>The Stream Deck MK.2 is a compact, weighted slab that measures about 4.6 inches wide, 3.3 inches deep, and 2 inches tall (with the stand extended). The weighted base and non-slip rubber feet keep it firmly planted on a desk — it does not slide when you press keys firmly. The included stand offers two tilt angles, and the detachable USB-C cable routes out the back for clean cable management.</p>

      <p>The detachable cable is the main upgrade over the original Stream Deck, which had a fixed cable that was prone to fraying at the strain relief. On the MK.2, if the cable breaks, you replace a $10 USB-C cable instead of the whole device. The cable is about 5 feet long, which is enough for most desk setups but short for a floor-mounted PC tower — plan your routing accordingly.</p>

      <p>Build quality is excellent. After 50 days of daily use, the keys showed no wear, the stand had no wobble, and the USB-C port had no looseness. The matte black plastic body resists fingerprints better than the original's glossy finish, and the whole device feels dense and well-constructed for $149. There is no wireless option — the Stream Deck requires a USB connection to the host computer, which limits placement on a clean desk.</p>

      <h3>Software and Plugin Ecosystem</h3>
      <p>The Elgato Stream Deck software is the heart of the device, and it is mostly excellent. The drag-and-drop action builder is intuitive, the profile manager is clean, and the plugin marketplace is integrated directly into the app. Updates are frequent — Elgato pushes new features and bug fixes every few weeks — but the software can be buggy after updates. We experienced one incident where profiles failed to load after an update, requiring a software restart to fix.</p>

      <p>The software is Windows and macOS only. There is no official Linux support, which is a real limitation for developers and creators running Linux workstations. Third-party open-source alternatives like StreamDeckUI exist for Linux, but they do not support all plugins and lack the polished UI of Elgato's official app. If you are on Linux, research the third-party options before buying.</p>

      <p>The plugin ecosystem is the Stream Deck's biggest long-term advantage. Elgato maintains an open plugin SDK, and the community has built thousands of integrations for apps ranging from OBS and Twitch to Adobe Creative Cloud, Microsoft Office, and smart home platforms. Most plugins are free, and the best ones are actively maintained by their developers. The ecosystem is what makes the Stream Deck a long-term investment rather than a one-trick device.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>The Stream Deck MK.2 competes against the Elgato Stream Deck XL, the Razer Stream Controller, and budget macro keypads. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Device</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Keys</th>
            <th>LCD</th>
            <th>Software</th>
            <th>Wireless</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Elgato Stream Deck MK.2</strong></td>
            <td>$149</td>
            <td>15</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Elgato</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Elgato Stream Deck XL</td>
            <td>$219</td>
            <td>32</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Elgato</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
