          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Elgato Stream Deck XL</strong> is the direct upgrade path. For $70 more, you get 32 keys instead of 15, which doubles your visible actions without folder nesting. If you do video editing with long timelines or complex streaming setups with dozens of scenes, the XL is worth it. For most users, 15 keys plus folders is enough — the XL is a luxury, not a necessity.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Razer Stream Controller</strong> (rebranded Loupedeck Live) is the cross-platform alternative. It costs $50 more, adds six touch-sensitive dials alongside the 15 keys, and uses Loupedeck's software, which some users prefer for timeline-based workflows. The trade-off is a smaller plugin ecosystem and more complex setup. For streamers, Elgato's software and community are the stronger pick; for video editors, the Razer's dials can be a real advantage.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Max Falcon-8</strong> is the budget alternative at $45. It has 8 mechanical keys (no LCD), runs open-source QMK firmware, and is wireless over Bluetooth. The trade-off is no LCD icons and no Elgato software — you program keys via the VIA web app, and there is no Smart Profile switching. For users who just need a few static macros, the Falcon-8 is a great value; for anyone who wants visual feedback and app-aware profiles, the Stream Deck wins.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Stream Deck MK.2 if you stream, edit video, or run repetitive workflows daily and want one-press access to your most-used actions. The LCD keys, Smart Profiles, and Multi Actions pay for themselves in saved clicks within a few months for power users.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. Elgato runs promotions around Prime Day and Black Friday where the MK.2 drops to $119 to $129. The savings are modest but real, and the Stream Deck XL sometimes drops to $189 during the same sales, making the upgrade more affordable.</p>

      <p>Consider the Stream Deck XL instead if you already know you need more than 15 keys visible at once. The XL costs $70 more and doubles your key count, which is worth it for video editors and complex streaming setups. If you are new to macro pads, start with the 15-key MK.2 — most users do not need the XL.</p>

      <p>Skip the Stream Deck and buy a budget macro keypad if you only need a few static shortcuts. The Max Falcon-8 ($45) or a generic 6-key macro pad ($25) will handle basic launches and muting without the LCD or Smart Profiles. You can always upgrade later if you outgrow the basic pad.</p>

      <p>Plan your desk layout before buying. The Stream Deck is wired-only, so it needs to sit within 5 feet of your computer. A <a href="/reviews/best-usb-c-hub-macbook/">USB-C hub</a> can extend your reach if your PC is far from your desk surface. Pair the Stream Deck with a <a href="/reviews/best-webcam-work-from-home/">good webcam</a> for a complete streaming or meeting setup.</p>

